                                </div></ulink></entry></row></tbody></tgroup></table><para> The format of the metadata records is the so-called MODS format, a standard for bibliographical description maintained by the US Library of
                Congress called "MODS" for Metadata Object Description Schema. </para><para> This standard allows one to catalogue many different kinds of material, not just books and articles, but web sites, photos, videos, maps,
                computer files and so on. It allows one to catalogue in great detail, but also to catalogue simplly. It allows one to relate one record (say, an
                entry for a book) to another entry (say an entry for a movie) and it allows one to make notes that one can "type" freely. </para><para>You don't have to make acquaintance with this format, but basically all it does is to surround each type of information with a set of tags,
                like <title>Midsummer Night's Dream</title></para><para>Further information on the MODS format can be found at <ulink url="http://www.loc.gov/standards/mods/" target="_blank">The Library of
            Congress</ulink>.</para></chapter></book>